  "doc_id": "48557",
  "text": "DNA translocases in replication fork protection and processing SMA RCAL1, ZRA NB3, and HLTF are ATPase-dependent DNA translocases of the SNF2 family of chromatin remodelers. These related proteins have been shown to have similar fork remodeling activity in vitro. SMA RCAL1 demonstrates affinity for DNA fork structures and catalyzes strand annealing, fork regression, and branch migration [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . ZRA NB3 and HLTF also catalyze replication fork reversal in vitro [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Recent work has further expanded the role of SMA RCAL1, ZRA NB3, and HLTF to replication fork reversal in vivo (Fig. 5) . is to regulate RAD51 activity at the replication fork to prevent unnecessary RAD51 association and fork remodeling during unperturbed DNA replication. Upon RADX depletion, there is increased genomic instability and DSBs that may be the result of inappropriate replication fork remodeling, leading to increased fork cleavage by MUS81. (B) The depletion of RADX in BRCA2deficient cells rescues nascent strand degradation at HU stalled replication forks without affecting homologous recombination. It is proposed that the removal of RADX results in increased RAD51 function, supporting improved RAD51 fork protection and the prevention of nascent strand degradation by nucleases.",
